<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0846-B"><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>&quot;When I was four, I saw the pope for the first time in Warsaw in 1979.</line><line>&quot;We want to be together with other people,&quot; said a young mother on the esplanade with her two children, aged one and six.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>Dzwigaj finished the monument four years ago but Krakow city authorities decided at the time not to place it in the cemetery.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0065"><line>Political and religious leaders as well as royals from around the world are expected to attend the funeral of Pope John Paul II on Friday at the Vatican.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="22,37"><scu uid="50" label="Mourners included state leaders." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>Cardinals are to meet in secret at a conclave beginning April 18 to elect a successor to the pontiff, who died a week ago after 26 years as leader of the Roman Catholic Church worldwide.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="0"><scu uid="48" label="Cardinals will meet on April 18 to elect a new pontiff" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>600 words 0600 GMT by Harmonie Toros.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050408.0810"><line>Malawi has more than 4 million Roman Catholics, making it the largest church in the southern African country.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0131"><line>Dignitaries from around the world stood in respect as the coffin was placed at the heart of the altar.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>500 words 0500 GMT</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>Friday's funeral mass for John Paul II was briefly interrupted when many in the crowd began chanting &quot;santo, santo&quot; repeatedly.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>Pictures    Vatican-pope-US-women,newseries  WASHINGTON  Pope John Paul II is credited for some advances by women in the Catholic Church, but his conservative social views have alienated many who have had difficulty reconciling Church doctrine with their everyday lives.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>More than the 20,000 people who usually live in Wadowice were gathered outside the town's basilica.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>&quot;In his lifetime, John Paul II worked to unite people.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>The Catholic Church has three steps to sainthood.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0131"><line>A red-bound New Testament was opened and placed on top of the coffin, its pages flickering in the wind, as funereal music played and Catholic prelates took their seats.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>Schudrich had taken part in John Paul II's funeral in Rome earlier Friday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="18,22,32,42"><scu uid="29" label="The funeral service for Pope John Paul II was held Friday, April 8." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>A monument to John Paul II was inaugurated Saturday at Rakowicki cemetery in Krakow, where the late pope's family are buried.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="9" sums="13,14,23,29,32,43,44,49,51"><scu uid="38" label="Members of John Paul II's family are buried in a Krakow cemetery." weight="3"/><scu uid="36" label="A monument was inaugurated immediately on Saturday in a cemetery in Krakow." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0065"><line>Naruhito, on behalf of his father Emperor Akihito, took a deep bow before a photograph of the pope as he offered a small bouquet of white flowers at St Mary's Cathedral.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>1,000 words 0530 GMT by Denis Barnett  We will also move: Vatican-pope-chrono  We have already moved: Vatican-pope-textament-text-excerpts    Vatican-pope-mass  VATICAN CITY  The requiem mass at the funeral of Pope John Paul II will follow centuries of solemn ritual befitting the final farewell to the spiritual leader of the world's 1.1 billion Roman Catholics.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>They, and the huge crowds gathered in towns, cities and villages elsewhere around the country, watched emotionally as John Paul II's simple wooden coffin, adorned with a cross and the M for Mary, was brought from Saint Peter's Basilica into the huge square outside and placed in front of an altar.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="52" label="The pope's body was placed in a plain wooden coffin." weight="1"/><scu uid="42" label="The pope's coffin was carried from Saint Peter's Basilica. " weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>&quot;We are here to once again sing our thanks for the pontificate of John Paul II,&quot; Bishop Jozef Guzek was quoted by Poland's PAP news agency as saying before the start of the funeral ceremony.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>450 words 0530 GMT  We will also move: Vatican-pope-basilica  Vatican-pope-crypt  Vatican-pope-grave    Vatican-pope-mourning-critics  PARIS  As the world prepares for the funeral of Pope John Paul II, some Europeans have questioned the deluge of ecstatic praise for the pontiff as well as the participation of scores of heads of state.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="50" label="Mourners included state leaders." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050408.0810"><line>President Bingu wa Mutharika declared Friday a national day of mourning for the late Pope John Paul II, allowing the faithful to attend special services.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="14,22,29,37,41,44,49,51"><scu uid="33" label="Friday was declared a national day of mourning in Malawi." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>In Warsaw, some 30,000 gathered in Pilsudski Square, another high holy place in John Paul II's pontificate.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,32,57"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>The final stage, canonisation, requires at least one more miracle.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>Monuments to the pope are to be erected in several cities and towns around Poland, including Wadowice in the south, where the pope was born Karol Wojtyla on May 18, 1920, and at Pilsudski Square in the capital, Warsaw.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="16,5"><scu uid="35" label="Monuments will be erected throughout Poland to honor the late Pope" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>Pope John Paul II's native Poland came to a standstill Friday as tolling bells and wailing sirens signalled the start of his funeral in distant Rome.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="9" sums="19,23,29,3,35,48,49,51,55"/></line><line>Those words were interpreted by many as an exhortation to stand up to the oppressive communist regime and allow a new Poland to be born.</line><line>He was bishop and cardinal of Krakow from 1963 until he was elected pope in 1978.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>On his visits as pope to his native Poland, John Paul II often prayed at the family grave at Rakowicki cemetery, where his parents and elder brother Edmund are buried.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="21,33"><scu uid="38" label="Members of John Paul II's family are buried in a Krakow cemetery." weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>Warsaw's Jewish community numbers some 400 people.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>With Friday declared a national holiday for the funeral, shops, local and international schools, banks, even the busy Warsaw stock exchange were shut.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>500 words moved    Vatican-pope-Poland  ROME  Amid cheers, applause and relief, six specially chartered trains arrive in the early hours at Rome's Ostiense station, delivering nearly 5,000 pilgrims from John Paul II's Polish homeland to the Italian capital for the pope's funeral.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="10,20,33"/></line><line>500 words moved by Carlos Diaz.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050408.0810"><line>The president, a Roman Catholic, attended a special mass in the capital, Lilongwe, where he praised John Paul as a man of peace and love.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0373"><line>The body of Pope John Paul II was laid to rest in the crypt of Saint Peter's basilica on Friday after an open-air funeral mass, Vatican officials said.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="6" sums="14,16,20,23,44,6"><scu uid="29" label="The funeral service for Pope John Paul II was held Friday, April 8." weight="3"/><scu uid="45" label="The pope was interred in the crypt of Saint Peter's Basilica." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>Schudrich has estimated the number of Jews living in Poland at between 30,000 and 40,000 -- only a fraction of the pre-war number of around 3.5 million.</line><line>We are all the children of God and a few hours ago, down there (in Rome) it worked -- we were really united,&quot; Schudrich told the gathering.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>Others held up large banners demanding &quot;santo subito&quot; (sainthood now) for a man who created more saints than all his predecessors put together.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>Pilsudski Square was one of the high holy places in John Paul II's pontificate, as it was there that on June 10, 1979 he uttered the memorable phrase: &quot;May the spirit come down and renew the face of this land.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>Most watched the ceremony without tears, their faces frozen in concentration as they took in the words and images of their favourite son before he was laid to rest.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>The next stage is beatification, which requires proof of a miracle as a result of his intercession.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0065"><line>Japan's Crown Price Naruhito joined 1,500 Catholics, diplomats and government officials at a Tokyo church Friday in a mass to mourn Pope John Paul II ahead of his funeral at the Vatican.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="11,12,25,33,37,47,55,6"><scu uid="55" label="In Japan, a mass was held to mourn for the pope" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>The 1.6-metre (five feet four inches) high bronze, by sculptor Czeslaw Dzwigaj, depicts the pope kneeling on a prie-dieu, or kneeling desk.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>The ecumenical prayer service was led by the Grand Rabbi of Poland, Michael Schudrich, Poland's PAP news agency said.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>Those words were interpreted by many Poles as an exhortation to stand up to the communist regime and allow a new Poland to be born.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>The spokesman, Joaquin Navarro-Valls, was speaking a day after the funeral of John Paul II, when a section of the massive crowd called for his immediate sainthood.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="0,19,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0126"><line>John Paul II died on April 2 in his private apartment in the Vatican after a 26-year pontificate.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>Following is the latest in our advisory series.</line><line>700 words moved by Stephanie Griffith    Vatican-pope-China-funeral  BEIJING  From the old official churches in Beijing to underground congregations in the countryside, China's Catholics mourn John Paul II as the late pope is buried in Rome.</line><line>As the world says a final farewell to Pope John Paul II at his solemn funeral Friday, we shall be regularly updating a package of stories throughout the day to mark the historic event.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="8" sums="10,12,20,21,25,36,40,5"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>In Krakow, some 800,000 pilgrims who had gathered on Blonia esplanade, a vast field on the city's periphery where the pope celebrated mass for some three million people on his last visit to Poland in 2002, fixed their gazes on specially erected giant screens showing live images from Rome.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0131"><line>Applause broke out as the plain cypress wood coffin was borne out of Saint Peter's Basilica by 12 bearers in black and placed on a small dais before the altar.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="16"><scu uid="54" label="The pope's coffin was placed before the altar." weight="2"/><scu uid="52" label="The pope's body was placed in a plain wooden coffin." weight="1"/><scu uid="42" label="The pope's coffin was carried from Saint Peter's Basilica. " weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0255"><line>The requiem mass for Pope John Paul II ended Friday at 12:30 pm (1030 GMT), drawing lengthy applause from the huge throng of mourners and state leaders massed on Saint Peter's Square.<annotation scu-count="4" sum-count="3" sums="14,43,44"><scu uid="29" label="The funeral service for Pope John Paul II was held Friday, April 8." weight="3"/><scu uid="41" label="The mourners applauded." weight="3"/><scu uid="40" label="There was a huge throng of mourners at the funeral." weight="3"/><scu uid="50" label="Mourners included state leaders." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>First is a ruling that the person concerned has led an exemplary life.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>In the capital Warsaw, trams and buses, and the few pedestrians in the streets, stopped in their tracks as tolling bells and moaning sirens signalled the start of the ceremony at 10:00 am (0800 GMT).</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>Pictures  We have also moved: Vatican-pope-Poland-tribute,lead    Vatican-pope-Cuba  HAVANA  Fidel Castro's faith in Marxism has not waned, even though the Cuban leader has allowed his communist-led island to officially mourn Pope John Paul II's passing.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050409.0157"><line>Only a new pope can beatify John Paul II, a Vatican spokesman said Saturday, saying any decision creating a saint was &quot;in the sole competency&quot; of the pope's successor.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="0"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>Before World War II the Polish capital had the second largest urban Jewish community in the world after New York City.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>It was there that, on June 10, 1979, the pope uttered the memorable phrase: &quot;May the spirit come down and renew the face of this land.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0131"><line>The funeral ceremony for Pope John Paul II began Friday in Saint Peter's Square in front of a seething mass of mourners and state leaders.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="12" sums="11,12,13,19,21,23,3,35,41,48,49,55"><scu uid="29" label="The funeral service for Pope John Paul II was held Friday, April 8." weight="3"/><scu uid="40" label="There was a huge throng of mourners at the funeral." weight="3"/><scu uid="50" label="Mourners included state leaders." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0600"><line>Several hundred people of all faiths prayed Friday evening at Warsaw synagogue for Polish-born Pope John Paul II, who was laid to rest in Rome.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="8" sums="11,22,29,32,42,43,51,57"><scu uid="51" label="Several hundred people of all faiths prayed at a Warsaw synagogue" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050408.0810"><line>All government offices, banks and businesses closed Friday, the day of the pope's funeral at the Vatican.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0065"><line>Japan has sent Yoriko Kawaguchi, special adviser to the prime minister and a former foreign minister.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>Many Poles chose to watch the ceremony from home, where it was beamed live from Rome by Polish television.</line><line>Near them, an empty chair was draped with yellow and white colours of the Vatican, appended with the black ribbon of mourning.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0065"><line>Highly secular Japan has a miniscule Christian community, although Pope John Paul II was well regarded for making a 1981 appeal for peace when he visited atomic-bombed Hiroshima and Nagasaki.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="42"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>700 words moved by Maja Czarnecka.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line><line>Vatican-pope-scene,lead  VATICAN CITY  Thousands of pilgrims wrapped in blankets, sleeping bags or their national flags sleep on the streets of Rome, eager to flood into St Peter's Square to say a final farewell at the funeral of Pope John Paul II.</line><line>Vatican-pope,2ndlead  VATICAN CITY  The world looks on Rome as leaders from more than 100 nations and a multitude of mourners gather in homage at the funeral of Pope John Paul II, one of the most cherished pontiffs of recent history.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>&quot;Time will dry our tears.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>Vatican-pope-obit  VATICAN CITY  Pope John Paul II revolutionised the papacy with his energy and intellectual ability but perhaps his most lasting memorial was his contribution to the collapse of communism in eastern Europe.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="25"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>John Paul II, who died on Saturday April 2, is widely credited with helping Poland to throw off the cloak of communism.</line><line>Sitting in the chair, John Paul II had bantered with inhabitants on his last visit to his birthplace in 1999.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="32,6"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>Pictures.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>John Paul II had special, close ties with Krakow, having studied in the former royal capital, been ordained as a priest there and celebrated his first mass at the city's Wawel Cathedral in 1946.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>1,000 words 0530 GMT by Kevin McElderry.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="10,13,21,36,40,41,43"><scu uid="44" label="The requiem mass followed centuries of solemn ritual" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0288"><line>I was with him then and I am sure my children want to be here now,&quot; she said.</line><line>We now transform our silence into prayer,&quot; he said.</line><line>Those who did venture outside sought the company of fellow mourners in places such as Blonia esplanade in Krakow, in front of the basilica of Our Lady in the southern town of Wadowice, where John Paul II was born Karol Wojtyla in 1920, or at Warsaw's Pilsudski and Zamkowy squares where giant screens had been set up.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050408.0008"><line>Pictures, graphic.</line></document></collection>